Title: Draft Fataluku Dictionary by Justino Valentim
Description.note: Draft Fataluku dictionary, researched and prepared by Justino Valentim, listing Fataluku words alphabetically alongside the  meaning of the word in Fataluku.  The draft contains handwritten annotations.  Words beginning with b, d,and g, are not listed; there are lists of words beginning with p, r, s and t, with no word meaning alongside. There are no words beginning with letter Q, V, X and Y in Fataluku.
Name.creator: Valentim, Justino (Cailoru)
Subject topic: Timor Leste languages|~|Fataluku language

Title: Hakarek Kona ba Timor Loro Sa'e - Fata-lukunu I Disionariu
AltTitle.other: Know About Timor Leste - Fataluku Dictionary
Contents note: The pamphlet is office printed, stapled and tape bound.
Description.note: In the Introduction, written in Fataluku, Justino Valentim explains that there are many different local languages spoken everyday in the Lautem District.  There are approximately 35,000 people who speak Fataluku, along with Saini ho Naine (approximately 12,000 speakers),and Makalero (approximately 12,000 speakers mostly from Iliomar).  Previously Makuwo language was spoken readily but it is now a lost language.  Mr Valentim hopes that the Fataluku dictionary presented, will help to preserve this local language into the future, and encourage others to continue researching the Fataluku language.
Name.creator: Valentim, Justino (Cailoru)
Subject topic: Timor Leste languages|~|Fataluku language

Title: Fataluku Waihohonu Aiknanoik 828
Contents note: This book was prepared in collaboration with Mr Michio Takahachi from the Timor Loro Sa'e-Nippon Culture Center (TNCC), who is now deceased.  Many attempts have been made to contact the Nippon Culture Center without success.  Known cultural collaborators were contacted about the project.
Description.note: This book documents 828 sung verses of Vaihoho from cultural collaborators in the Lautem District of Timor Leste.  Señor Valentim explains in the Fataluku language introduction that he was prompted to record Vaihoho (sung poems) because they were not practised or understood by younger generations, and are in danger of being lost.  The sung poems include descriptions of traditional marriage arrangements, and dealing with disagreements between different groups.
Name.creator: Valentim, Justino (Cailoru)
Place of origin: Titilari, Suco Fuiloro, Lospalos, Lautem District, Timor Leste
Subject topic: Timor Leste languages|~|Fataluku language|~|Fataluku sung poems|~|Vaihoho|~|Fataluku oral traditions

Title: Fataluku Vaihohonu

Description.note: This booklet documents Fataluku language Vaihoho (sung poems) handed down through generations. The sung poems cover various topics including forging good relationships between groups.

Title: Untitled Notes 2
Contents note: An example of halu vaihoho can be found at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mIOwcI85dL8&t=61s
Description.note: Thirteen loose pages previously held in a folder, with Vaihoho from Mr. Manuel Xisto.  The Vaihoho uses metaphoric language to depict romantic relationships, traditional marriage, and the plight of orphans.  Pages _0012 and _0013 deal directly with the Indonesian invasion and occupation. Halu vaihoho (war song) tell about the tragedy of the conflict and massacres involved when Indonesia occupied Timor Leste. Many people were killed, but some were able to escape by hiding in forest areas.
Name.creator: Valentim, Justino (Cailoru)
Subject topic: Timor Leste languages|~|Fataluku language|~|Fataluku sung poems|~|Vaihoho|~|Fataluku oral traditions

Title: Untitled Book - Mr. Orlando
Description.note: Transcriptions of Vaihoho by Senor Valentim recorded in an exercise book.  Senor Gonsalves (deceased) is the knowledge holder.  The languauge is in high Fataluku, which few people now use or understand.  Content of the sung poems is in two parts.  Up to verse 26 are poems for the Cailoru tribal people, detailing local places, traditional names of people and orphan farewells.  From verse 27 the vaihoho are about romantic relations among young girls and young boys.
Name.creator: Valentim, Justino (Cailoru)|~|Gonsalves, Orlando (Cailoro)
Subject topic: Timor Leste languages|~|Fataluku language|~|Fataluku sung poems|~|Vaihoho|~|Fataluku oral traditions

Title: Untitled Book - Mr. Inacio (Ira-Ara/Larinu)
Contents note: Senhor Inacio Conceiçāo is an elder from the sub-village of Ira-Ara in Lospalos.  He is from the Naza Ratu (tribe).
Description.note: Transcription of tradiitional vaihoho by Senhor Valentim, from Senhor Inacio da Conceiçāo.  The language is high, ritual Fataluku. (_0003) 'En iharala vaihoho' is about traditional marriage and 'Hini vaihoho' is an orphan's lament; (_0004) 'En orontafan i vaihoho' is about husking rice; (_0005 and _0006) 'Ete seilana (Ete seilen) Leuli vaihoho' is about hauling logs from the forest, that will be used to make a traditional house (Uma Lulik); (_0007) 'Txele Sipilen vaihoho' about harvesting corn together, call and response in conjunction with _0008; (_0008) 'Txele Sipilana vaihoho' response to _0007. (_0009) 'Aletielen Leuli vaihoho' about rice harvesting. (_0010 and _0011) call and response vaihoho.
Name.creator: Valentim, Justino (Cailoru)|~|da Conceiçāo, Inacio (Nazaratu)
Subject topic: Timor Leste languages|~|Fataluku language|~|Fataluku sung poems|~|Vaihoho|~|Fataluku oral traditions

Title: Untitled Book - Inacio Conceição 2
Description.note: This is the second notebook from Senhor Inacio Da Conceiçāo obtained by Senhor Justino Valentim, documenting vaihoho sung poems (First notebook is jv_vaihoho_0008).   This notebook describes vaihoho from the Pitileti Naza ratu (tribe) from Ira-Ara sub-village in Lospalos. Most of the Vaihoho are in high Fataluku and include Vaihoho sung at traditional marriage ceremonies, references traditional names and working songs.  Pages _0003, _0004,  _0029 and _0030, use everyday Fataluku and are about the war and Indonesian occupation.
Name.creator: Valentim, Justino (Cailoru)|~|da Conceição, Inacio (Nazaratu)
Subject topic: Timor Leste languages|~|Fataluku language|~|Fataluku sung poems|~|Vaihoho|~|Fataluku oral traditions

Title: Rata Waihohonu
Description.note: Annotated typed pages of Vaihoho using high Fataluku.  Topics include relationships between different villages, orphan's laments, traditional marriages, ceremonies for traditional sacred house (Uma Lulik).  The additional handwritten verses on the first page use everyday Fataluku and are affectionate goodbyes.
Name.creator: Valentim, Justino (Cailoru)

Title: Untitled Book 2
Contents note: Lospalos is the sub-district of the Lautem District, which is the home district of the Fataluku speaking people of Timor Leste; Lospalos, the town, is also the administrative capital of the Lautem District. This book also includes an inserted supplementary page of handwritten Vaihoho verses which deal with the natural world.
Description.note: Hand written notebook containing Fataluku Vaihoho sung poems with some translated into Tetum.  The subject of the poems is the beautiful country of Timor Leste. Page _0003 English translation of the Tetum (on right hand side): Lospalos Lospalos; Where is Lospalos; In the good country; With mountains all around
Name.creator: Valentim, Justino (Cailoru)
